"Yes, sir. They should be on their way now, we gave them time to get rations from the mess." Exactly at 5:00, the Exodus company was gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying to the FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to crush the insurrection. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units, and embark."
The company dispersed, each joining their unit, and the sergeants made them board the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side, legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, does Harris still have Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren jeta un œil vers l'un des chars et aperçut Harris avec son unité. De l'arrière de son paquetage, il pouvait juste distinguer le mouvement d'un petit poulet agitant la tête pour observer les environs.
"Ouais, il l'a toujours", répondit Cohren alors que la tourelle du char s'ouvrait dans un cliquetis pour laisser passer son commandant.
"Tous les chars étaient en route", déclara calmement, mais clairement le commandant dans son casque. Les moteurs d'un peloton de chars et de Strykers rugirent tandis qu'ils commençaient à avancer. Le Kronos sur lequel Cohren se trouvait eut une secousse quand ses freins furent desserrés et qu'il se mit en marche pour se mettre en formation. Les chars se déployèrent en V pour traverser les plaines d'Itania. Les tempêtes de l'hiver avaient gelé les marécages et les forêts, mais la boue était toujours là.
Après environ une heure, une des nouvelles recrues, du nom d'Orson dans le souvenir de Cohren, prit la parole. "Lieutenant, vous êtes ici depuis le début de la guerre, n'est-ce-pas ?"
"Ouep, Opération Tempête de feu", répondit Cohren. "Nous pensions en venir à bout en quelques semaines, mais... nous les avons sous-estimés."
"Underestimating is a weak word," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we had anticipated. They managed to destroy the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Christ, we should see it from where we are."
"Well, I'll hold firm for the Federation," said Orson a bit provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that young recruits like you, 18 years old, take cover the moment they hear a shot," declared Craith.
"I think we'll be soon settled," said Corhen laughing. Orson didn't respond to the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We detect thermal signatures approximately 300 meters, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed to the top of the tank and put on his optical glasses. Activating the thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yeah, I see them," replied Cohren through his throat mic.
"Enemies?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Can't say for sure," declared Cohren. He activated his mic and said: "Exodus Company, don't fire unless we're fired upon, make them come out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures went from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran towards something, picked it up, then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took up firing positions.
"We have contacts," shouted Shaw on the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. Bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while soldiers jumped from vehicles to take cover behind. A anti-tank missile whistled past and crashed to the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris flying across one of the vehicles. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew climbed out and dove for cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2 and &-", 25 degrees right, 275 meters. "Fire," roared the commander of the tank platoon over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew toward the ridge and exploded, sending mud and stones into the air.
"Send the Senti," shouted Knoxx, who was observing the ridge through his binoculars. The back of one of the Cerberus opened and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet exited. He bellowed orders into a square microphone and two Senti, or Sentinels by their official name, rushed out. Their thin metal arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?" asked Craith as they watched them.
"It seems we capture them," advanced Cohren as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of ash and smoke. Screams and gunshots echoed from the ridge, but quickly ceased. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged along the ground. Once safe with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked towards the individual, who was beginning to get up. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," replied the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned towards Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you be so kind as to get rid of this man?"
